<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: MPs give warning on housing cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE on the government to maintain the present level of housing
association grants mounted yesterday with the publication of a Commons
environment committee report warning that cuts would put decent housing
beyond the reach of many families.
The report, which says that ministers must consider the wider social
consequences of short-term budget savings, was welcomed by Sir George Young,
the housing minister.
Sir George faces a fight to protect housing association budgets in the
forthcoming spending round negotiations with the Treasury, which has
identified housing expenditure as an area for possible savings.
He said he would assess carefully the implications of the committee's report
and expected to publish his response after the summer recess.
The report says that previously published government plans to reduce housing
association grant rates from the current 67 per cent to 55 per cent by
1995-96 would prevent some associations from building homes and leave many
tenants facing higher rents. MPs say the government should therefore drop
the planned cuts.
Ministers are also urged to set up a working party to review the
relationship between housing association grants and housing benefit
entitlements - and to develop a strategy for easing the problems faced by
tenants caught in the poverty trap.
Mr John Battle, Labour's housing spokesman, said housing associations needed
an end to the uncertainty surrounding their future so that they could
attract additional private finance. Tenants needed to know that their rents
were not going to 'rocket' because of grant cuts.
Mr Jim Coulter, director of the National Federation of Housing Associations,
said the report confirmed that the government was stifling the potential
growth of social housing. 'We call on the minister to announce that housing
association grant rates will not be reduced in the coming two years'.
