<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major accepts Pounds 1,001 in libel
case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR said last night that his libel case with New Statesman and
Society magazine had been settled and that he had accepted damages of Pounds
1,001. 'Having regard to substantial damages already received from the
printers and distributors, I am content to accept the additional sum paid
into court by the New Statesman, together with my costs as a settlement to
this action,' Mr Major said in a statement from the G7 meeting in Tokyo.
The statement was issued after the magazine had stated that actions by Mr
Major and caterer Ms Clare Latimer had been settled, each with a payment of
Pounds 1,001.
The action arose out of an article published in the magazine in January
which linked Mr Major to Ms Clare Latimer. Mr Major had demanded substantial
compensation for libel after rejecting as unacceptable a statement of
explanation published in the magazine the following month.
The magazine said it considered the conclusion of the action vindicated its
opinion that the article was not defamatory. It claimed that total costs to
the magazine arising from actions taken over the article now exceeded Pounds
200,000.
A settlement means that the prime minister will not have to appear in court
in support of his action. He would have become the first prime minister to
enter the witness box in a libel case.
Mr Major has already concluded libel actions against the distributor of the
magazine and two wholesalers.
A poll in today's Guardian shows Mr Major to have the lowest-recorded
personal popularity rating for a serving prime minister.
The ICM poll says Mr Major is seen as incompetent with 'no clear idea of
where he is leading the government'. His popularity rating - at just 14 per
cent - is well below Baroness Thatcher's lowest-ever recording in April 1990
when she scored 23 per cent.
</TEXT>
