FT  07 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government support for councils may
move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHIFT in government support for councils away from inner cities towards
rural areas will take place next spring unless ministers act to mitigate its
effect, Alison Smith writes.
The review of the basis on which the government allocates grant, together
with the use of the full information from the 1991 census, suggests that
some urban councils could lose up to 20 per cent of their grant.
Ministers acknowledge that such a change could not be allowed to happen in a
single year. Apart from difficulty for local authorities, the London local
elections in May next year are another reason to soften the impact.
Figures indicate that some London boroughs, including flagship Tory councils
Westminster and Wandsworth, would lose between 10 per cent and 14 per cent
of their standard spending assessments.
