<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Funding set for shift to rural
areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SUBSTANTIAL shift in government support for local councils, away from
inner cities and towards rural areas, will take place next spring, unless
ministers act to mitigate its effect.
The review of the basis on which the government allocates grant, together
with the use of the full information from the 1991 census, suggests that
some urban councils could lose up to 20 per cent of their grant.
Ministers acknowledge that such a stark change could not be allowed to
happen in a single year. Apart from the sheer difficulty for local
authorities of such a large adjustment, the London local elections in May
next year provide a further reason to soften the impact.
Simply updating the formula by which the government decides how much it
thinks councils should spend, recent government figures indicate that some
inner London boroughs, including the flagship Tory councils in Westminster
and Wandsworth, would lose between 10 per cent and 14 per cent of their
standard spending assessments.
On the same basis, more remote - mainly rural - districts could gain by just
over 13 per cent in their SSAs.
The review of SSAs is set to intensify this shift.
Less weight is expected to be given in the system to factors such as
ethnicity. Double-counting is also expected to be cut: at present, for
example, there are separate factors for the number of lone parents in an
area and the number of people on income support, even though the two groups
over-lap.
The Department of the Environment admits that these figures will not be
reflected in the grant settlement for next year.
Instead, ministers are likely to agree on some form of separate grant,
similar to the one operating this year.
That grant compensates councils which lost more than 5 per cent of their
grant because of the fall in population revealed by use of the basic 1991
census data.
</TEXT>
