<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Proposals on sentence discounting welcomed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'sentence discounting' recommended by the royal commission would extend
and clarify current arrangements to secure a guilty plea before a trial
begins.
At present, a judge can be approached by a defendant's lawyers for an
indication only of whether or not he or she has a custodial sentence in
mind. Judges cannot say how long a prison sentence they may be considering.
Rough tariffs for offences are accepted and the standard discount for an
early plea is a one third reduction in the size of a sentence.
This discount applies for all kinds of criminal offences across the board.
On some occasions - such as when co-operation is provided in investigations
into organised crime - the discounts can be substantially higher.
The sentence discounting proposed by the commission would extend this by
allowing judges to indicate the length of prison sentences they were
considering at that point in the proceedings.
This is welcomed by some lawyers as avoiding problems when judges impose
sentences that differ from those on the normally accepted tariff.
It falls considerably short, however, of the US system of plea-bargaining
where prosecutors are in effect able to offer sentence reductions in return
for co-operation in their inquiries. Lord Runciman yesterday made clear that
the commission rejected this scenario and stuck firmly to the view that
sentencing remained a responsibility of the judiciary, not prosecutors.
The commission proposed safeguards to prevent the innocent feeling under
pressure to plead guilty to offences they have not committed. The
discounting procedure would be instigated by the defendant only. The meeting
with the judge would be heard in camera and formally noted to avoid later
confusion.
The commission's proposals have been welcomed by some lawyers as an
improvement on present arrangements. Others are less convinced. Mr Michael
Mansfield QC is among those who argue it is likely to lead to more wrongful
convictions as pressure is inevitably applied on the innocent to plead
guilty.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
