<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / House prices 'decline 1.1%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE PRICES fell by 1.1 per cent in June, Halifax, the country's biggest
building society, said yesterday. The society said it was the second monthly
fall in succession.
The findings conflict with figures published by Nationwide, the second
largest society, which reported that prices rose 1.6 per cent in June, the
fourth consecutive monthly price rise recorded by the society.
Halifax, unlike Nationwide, adjusts its figures to take account of seasonal
variations. It said that if figures from both societies were 'averaged out',
they would show very little movement since last September: 'House prices are
unlikely to show consistent rises until there is firmer evidence of rising
demand for mortgage finance and increased levels of transactions.'
Housebuilders have expressed concern that the revival in house sales has
faltered in recent weeks.
Sir Brian Hill, president of the Building Employers Confederation, said on
Monday that a lack of consumer confidence was having a 'particularly severe
impact on the private housing market which, having shown an improvement in
prospects in the spring, has now faltered'.
Halifax said it expected increased demand for mortgages to feed through to
gradual increases in house prices in the second half of this year.
It added that prices should rise more steadily next year, increasing by
about 5 per cent.
Halifax said the average price of a house last month was Pounds 62,440 - 4.5
per cent lower than 12 months ago.
</TEXT>
