<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / SFO call for US-style plea bargains rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CALLS BY the Serious Fraud Office for a US-style of plea-bargaining to help
reduce the number of controversial City 'mega-trials' have been rejected by
the Royal Commission.
Instead, the commission recommended a system of 'sentence discounts' for
defendants in all criminal proceedings willing to plead guilty before a
trial starts.
However, it stopped far short of agreeing with the SFO that prosecutors
should have an active role in offering lower sentences to suspects in
exchange for increased co-operation.
Mr George Staple, the director of the SFO, had argued that the introduction
of formal plea bargaining was the most effective way of shortening the
process of prosecuting fraud.
This was rejected by the commission as too extreme. Lord Runciman yesterday
emphasised the commission's view that sentencing issues should be determined
by judges alone with prosecutors playing no role in deciding penalties.
The commission suggested a number of improvements to the investigation and
prosecution of fraud cases, including forcing defence teams to give a
detailed outline of their cases at an earlier stage.
However, the general reaction of lawyers was that the commission had
addressed matters of detail rather than proposing major reform and that its
proposals, if implemented, would have only marginal impact on the problem of
the large fraud trial. This, as one lawyer said, reflected the 'bolting on'
of fraud trial reform to the commission's agenda after it had begun
addressing its central concern of miscarriages of justice.
The SFO welcomed the report, saying it was pleased the commission had
reflected some of its views.
Recommendations made by the commission for the investigation and prosecution
of fraud include:
Greater disclosure by defence lawyers of their clients' case to the
prosecution before the trial starts. Defence lawyers can now say merely that
they oppose the prosecution's case. They should have to state their attitude
on individual details of the prosecution case, the commission suggests.
Trial by jury should remain.
The 'Section 2' powers of the SFO, which remove the right to silence and
compel witnesses to answer questions - should be extended to allow police
officers, as well as SFO lawyers and accountants, to carry out such
interviews. Evidence gathered in Section 2 interviews should remain
inadmissible in court, unless it contradicts evidence given in court by a
defendant.
A feasibility study should be carried out into the possible merging of the
SFO with the Fraud Investigation Group. The commission said there was no
justification for the group, which is part of the Crown Prosecution Service,
not having the same Section 2 powers as the SFO.
Time limits on fraud trials could be introduced, provided they remained
flexible.
Judges should be able to outline a case's basic issues to the jury at the
start of a trial.
Fraud defendants should be able to be able to plead guilty to a serious
regulatory offence subject to the disciplinary sanctions of the Securities
and Investments Board, rather than face criminal charges, although this
should only be available in a strictly limited type of case.
Reactions among fraud solicitors were muted.
Mr John Clitheroe of Kingsley Napley said the recommendations would not
fundamentally advance the present state of affairs. However, he questioned
the wisdom of suggesting police carry out Section 2 interviews when they
also carried out the interviews with suspects which could later be used as
evidence in court.
Mr Anthony Vernon of Richards Butler said sentence discounts would have less
effect with fraud than in other types of crime. With fraud, the issues
involved often only became clear at a comparatively late stage. To encourage
early guilty pleas in these circumstances might amount to undesirable
'horse-trading', he said.
</TEXT>
