<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Social Chapter opt-out defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALASTAIR Goodlad, Foreign Office minister, yesterday launched a fierce
defence of Britain's opt-out from the Social Chapter of the Maastricht
agreement. He insisted that future European success in the face of fierce
competition from east Asia depended on flexibility for employers over wage
rates, and over where to locate.
'We face a choice between a flexible and competitive life, or an
accelerating economic death by drowning in a sea of regulation and rising
costs,' Mr Goodlad said in a speech to the London Chamber of Commerce.
The EC's annual labour report, due to be published today, is expected to
attack Britain's claim that rising social welfare costs hurt
competitiveness.  Mr Goodlad's comments appear aimed at deflecting this
criticism.
'Rising wages, unaccompanied by higher productivity, mean only one thing -
unemployment,' Mr Goodlad said. He pinpointed 'three arresting trends':
EC member states are selling more to each other, are selling less outside
the EC, and are importing more.
Rising labour costs are making European companies less competitive.
Slow growth in Europe is a symptom of declining competitiveness.
'The last thing we need is new, extensive, and burdensome social
harmonisation,' he added. 'That would wreck our competitive position.'
</TEXT>
