<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Prescott criticises City cordon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Prescott, shadow transport secretary, yesterday strongly criticised
the City's anti-terrorist cordon. He said the City authorities had not
consulted other traffic authorities before implementing the controversial
scheme, Gillian Tett writes.
Echoing concern in some Whitehall departments, he said that neither the
traffic director for London nor London Transport had been consulted by the
police.
Commander Hugh Moore of the City of London Police said: 'The consultation
period had to be limited because of the security issues.'
The Corporation of London said the new scheme had been a complete success
and pointed out that the widely predicted traffic congestion had failed to
materialise so far.
However, Mr Prescott insisted the situation could rapidly deteriorate. He
said: 'We are entering the summer holiday period when many people are not
travelling to work. When everybody returns it will be a different story, and
it will be traffic chaos.'
