<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Warning over contracting out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT could face retrospective claims from tens of thousands of
public service workers who experienced a deterioration in pay and conditions
when their jobs were contracted out to the private sector.
Mr Jack Dromey, a national secretary of the TGWU general union, told the
union's conference yesterday that hundreds of test cases were being prepared
and would go to court if the government rejected a general settlement.
The issue has arisen because of the European Community's Tupe legislation
which protects the pay and conditions of workers in many cases of job
transfer.
Although Tupe has been part of British law since 1981, it is only recently
that the government has acknowledged that its provisions can apply to
contracting out.
Mr Dromey says that up to 25,000 workers in local and central government and
the National Health Service had their pay reduced before it was realised
that they were protected by Tupe and that the government should now pay up.
The compensation sums involved are estimated to be in the tens of millions
of pounds and Mr Dromey said that the government faced the prospect of
spending more than that in legal fees if it did not agree a settlement.
He added: 'The government has a choice over Tupe - an expensive decade of
chaos or a settlement.'
</TEXT>
