<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 93 / Back to basics for healthcare: The World Bank says that
child mortality rates remain 10 times as high as in the richest countries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEVELOPING countries could reduce the burden of disease by up to a third by
spending less on high-tech medicine and more on basic public health and
clinical services the World Bank says in its latest World Development
Report.
The report, published today, says the high incidence of disease and
disability is caused as much by the poor allocation of existing resources as
by a lack of funds. In some countries, one teaching hospital, catering
mainly for the affluent, can absorb 20 per cent or more of the national
healthcare budget.
The report urges poor and middle income countries to invest in a minimum
healthcare package comprising routine public health measures and a few
essential clinical services. Such services could be provided by local
clinics and district hospitals and would not need expensive equipment or
highly-trained specialists.
On public health, the most cost-effective measures include expanding
immunisation services for children, school-based health services, campaigns
to reduce levels of smoking and alcohol consumption, information about
nutrition and family planning, and efforts to prevent the spread of Aids.
Clinical services should include at least prenatal and delivery care, family
planning, tuberculosis control, care for childhood diseases and simple
treatments for sexually-transmitted diseases. Hospital- based emergency care
should be provided depending on capacity and resources.
In the poorest countries, the cost of this minimum package *something in
here (HP) *
would be about Dollars 12 per person a year, or just over 3 per cent of per
capita income. Bank estimates indicate this modest investment could reduce
the burden of disease by more than 30 per cent. In middle income countries,
the minimum package would cost about Dollars 22 per person or roughly 1 per
cent of per capita incomes. It could reduce the burden of disease by about
15 per cent.
Adopting the package in all developing countries would require a quadrupling
of expenditure on public health, from about Dollars 5bn to Dollars 20bn a
year, and a doubling of spending on essential clinical services to Dollars
40bn.
In middle income countries, where public healthcare expenditure is already
about Dollars 60 per person a year, the package could be financed out of
existing resources provided existing spending on less cost-effective
discretionary services, such as heart surgery, was reduced.
In the poorest countries public spending on healthcare is only about Dollars
6 per person a year. The bank's minimum package would thus require a
substantial increase in spending by governments, donors and patients, as
well as a redirection of the healthcare budget from specialised facilities
for the affluent.
Such measures would work best if accompanied by broader efforts to reduce
household poverty and improve education, the report says.
Studies show people with more schooling utilise health information more
effectively than those without. 'Education of girls and women is
particularly beneficial to household health because it is largely women who
buy and prepare food, and initiate contacts with the health system.'
The bank emphasises the importance of promoting diversity and competition in
the supply of health services. In the short term, reforms in drug
procurement offer the greatest efficiency gains. Governments that have
introduced competition in drug procurement and switched from brand name to
generic drugs have achieved savings of 40-60 per cent.
The report says developing countries have made great strides in improving
health conditions. In the past four decades, life expectancy has risen from
40 years to 63 years and the number of children dying before their fifth
birthday has dropped from nearly three in 10 to one in 10.
However, child mortality rates remain about 10 times as high as the richest
countries while maternal mortality rates can be up to 30 times higher.
In the past 6 years, the bank has quadrupled to Dollars 1.5bn a year its
lending for healthcare services in poor countries. If diseases such as Aids
and tuberculosis are to be controlled, other donors and institutions need to
put greater emphasis on supporting cost-effective health services, it says.
Investing in health. The 1993 WDR is available from The World Bank, 1818 H
Street, NW Washington DC 20433.
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
<XX>
