<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: 'We're after the bits that make a
profit' / A look at a coal company seeking high returns from rock-bottom
costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE weed-covered railway line which winds its way up the Neath Valley in
South Wales will shortly be clanking with wagons again.
Ryan Group, the privately-owned coal company, is restoring the track with a
Pounds 4m grant from the Welsh Office so it can haul coal from its Lyn and
Pentreclwydau mines. Ryan expects that when fully developed the two sites
will be the largest private underground mines in the UK, producing 600,000
tonnes to 700,000 tonnes of anthracite a year between them.
As the UK coal industry shakes itself out with the imminent privatisation of
British Coal, Mr Crispian Hotson, Ryan's South African-born chief executive,
says: 'We're not after the massive tonnages. We're after the bits that make
a profit.'
Ryan was originally a publicly quoted company which grew by recovering coal
dumped by collieries in the River Usk. But by the mid 1980s it was
loss-making and deeply in debt. Mr Hotson and his business partners injected
capital and took over management control, eventually buying the company in
1988.
Last year Ryan refinanced itself with Pounds 50m of equity from Electra, the
venture capital group, Bankers Trust and Creditanstalt Bankverein of
Austria, enabling it to reduce its large bank debts and get its balance
sheet in order. Mr Hotson expects to see annual losses of more than Pounds
4m transformed into a profit of Pounds 7m this year.
Following a radical restructuring which involved sales and closures, Ryan
now has three divisions. The largest is opencast mining, where its
subsidiary, Crouch Mining, produces 4m tonnes a year under contract for
British Coal. It also has a subsidiary in Pennsylvania which mines coal for
local utilities. The underground mining division is responsible for the
Neath Valley operations, and the third division is engaged in coal recovery
in Belgium and Poland.
Mr Hotson's vision of the future is based on a competitive coal industry
operating at a fraction of the costs of British Coal. With present trends,
Mr Hotson sees the UK coal industry shrinking to about 40m tonnes a year
(from 76m last year) by the year 2000. About half of that would come from
opencast operations, 16m from British Coal pits, and 4m from privately-owned
underground mines.
Mr Hotson thinks output from the underground mines could be raised to 30m to
40m tonnes if the private sector were given free rein to drive down costs
and introduce efficient working practices. In that case the UK could not
only wipe out imports, but might even export coal again.
Ryan expects to be among the bidders for licences from British Coal to
operate mines which the state-owned company cannot afford to keep open. None
of those currently on offer is of interest, but Mr Hotson says Ryan might
bid for Betws, the small south Wales anthracite mine, and 'one or two pits
in Nottinghamshire'.
He is looking for mines with 20 to 30 years of reserves, where Ryan can use
new techniques to get production costs below Pounds 1 a gigajoule, compared
with the Pounds 1.53 at which British Coal is supplying the generators. Ryan
is producing coal from open-cast mines for 60p a gigajoule.
At these lower prices, Mr Hotson says, domestically produced coal will not
only drive out imports but also compete strongly with alternative fuels,
particularly natural gas which poses the greatest threat to coal. He
believes that cheap coal could trigger the construction of a new generation
of coal-fired power stations using efficient clean coal technology.
Instead of the familiar giants, these would be small stations with a
capacity of as little at 200MW each. Ryan might get into the electricity
generation business itself if it can find suitable partners.
The recent flotation of another privately-owned coal mining group, RJB
Mining, has raised speculation that Ryan might try the same. But Ryan has
yet to build up its profit record. Also, Mr Hotson would rather bide his
time. The muted welcome given to RJB by the stock market suggested that the
outlook for private mining is still too clouded to fire investors'
enthusiasm.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ryan International.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1222 Bituminous Coal-Underground.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
