<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Foreign Exchanges: Franc under more pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FRENCH franc yesterday came under more pressure inside the European
exchange rate mechanism as dealers took the view that France will find it
hard to live with the current pace of Bundesbank interest rate cutting for
much longer, writes James Blitz.
Last week, the Bundesbank reduced its discount rate by 50 basis points to
6.75 per cent, in a move which added to hopes that European monetary policy
was easing and that tensions in the ERM had subsided once and for all.
However, the Bank of France almost immediately took advantage of the German
cut, bringing its intervention rate down to Germany's discount rate level
last Friday. Some dealers argued yesterday that the speed with which the
French authorities followed the German move suggested that France would do
what ever was necessary to ease monetary policy and boost the economy.
That sentiment has pushed the franc nearly two centimes lower against the
D-Mark in the last week, to finish yesterday at FFr3.386 from a close on
Friday night of FFr3.383. On its ERM divergence indicator, the franc ended
yesterday at a remarkably low level of minus 61 percentage points.
The French franc has partly been undermined by a broader feeling in foreign
exchange markets that Europe's central banks have been too ambitious in
trying to decouple their monetary policies from the Bundesbank.
The Bundesbank cut - and signs that M3 money supply growth is falling into
line with Bundesbank targets - helped to strengthen the D-Mark against
several European currencies yesterday.
The Danish krone closed a touch weaker at DKr3.8483 per D-Mark. The
divergence between the Dutch guilder and the D-Mark also narrowed, to 36
basis points, having been as high as  1/2 percentage point in recent weeks.
Even the dollar has shown signs of weakness against the D-Mark, after
breaking through the key level of DM1.67 three weeks ago: although last
night it closed in London unchanged on the day at DM1.6960.
However, the French franc appears particularly vulnerable, having been
undermined by a rising tide of grim economic news. Mr Jim O'Neill, head of
research at Swiss Banking Corporation, said the French economy is undermined
by bad consumer expenditure and corporate earnings figures, and a belief
that the government of Mr Edouard Balladur, the French prime minister, has
only a limited window of opportunity to boost the economy before the
presidential elections due in 1995.
Sterling was the one currency to perform strongly against the D-Mark
yesterday, rising  1/2 pfennig on the day to close at DM2.5625. The currency
was helped by higher than expected figures for net consumer credit in May,
and a report from Treasury advisers showing that the UK was set for above
trend growth.
</TEXT>
