<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For the past couple of years it has been very cheap to make movies in the
countries of the former communist bloc, and now they are beginning to arrive
on screen. An Exchange Of Fire is a two-part thriller set in Prague and
London, starring Frank Finlay as 'the ruthless head of a terrorist cell'.
The president of an east European state sends his daughter to the west where
she becomes mixed up in a kidnap plot . . . you get the picture. Part 2 is
screened tomorrow evening (10.00 C4).
First Tuesday investigates 'the worst terrorist outrage of the Anglo-Irish
troubles': the explosion of four car bombs in Dublin and Monaghan 19 years
ago. There were 33 deaths and nearly 300 were injured, but nobody has ever
been arrested for the crimes, let alone convicted. The producers promise to
'reveal the hidden truths behind the bombings and explain why details have
been buried', so it does not sound as though they will be saying who did it
(10.40 ITV).
BBC2 begins a new series about environmental issues: Nature (8.00) starting
with a report on possible health risks arising from the fluoridation of
water.
</TEXT>
