<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / ITV digs in over News at Ten scheduling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ITV companies yesterday declined to back down publicly over the
scheduling of News at Ten in spite of the political furore caused by
proposals to move it to an early evening slot.
The ITV Council, which brings together the chief executives of the 15
regional ITV companies, decided it wanted to meet the Independent Television
Commission 'to review the extensive research on this issue and its
commercial implications'.
In a carefully worded statement the ITV companies said they wanted to
explore different interpretations of the 1990 Broadcasting Act over the
scheduling of news programmes.
The future of News at Ten will be discussed by the ITC on July 14 at the
previously scheduled annual meeting between the members of the commission
and the chief executives of ITV.
There is no sign, however, that the ITC is prepared to compromise on the
issue. The commission, which saw yesterday's ITV statement as a face-saving
exercise, will stick to its line that no change in the scheduling of News at
Ten is possible without its approval.
It is difficult to see what ITV can do, even though it has a strong legal
opinion that the ITC does not have the right to specify a particular time
for the main evening news other than 'prime time' between 6.30pm and 10pm.
To force the issue forward ITV would have to decide unilaterally to move
News at Ten.
The companies would then almost certainly face stiff fines from the ITC for
breaches of their licences. Only then could they challenge the ITC in the
High Court by seeking a judicial review of such a deci-sion.
In spite of yesterday's show of defiance the odds are that News at Ten will
stay where it is for the forseeable future.
ITV company Yorkshire-Tyne Tees is to axe 188 jobs as part of a cost-cutting
drive, it announced yesterday.
</TEXT>
