<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Teachers continue boycott of tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TWO largest teachers' unions yesterday said members would continue
boycotting national curriculum tests in September.
This intensifies pressure for drastic changes to the tests. A review being
conducted by Sir Ron Dearing, chairman designate of the Schools Curriculum
and Assessment Authority, is expected to produce preliminary conclusions at
the end of the month.
Boycotts by the three main teachers' unions this year meant that scarcely
any pupils took the tests.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, made clear his union would end the
boycott if the review cut their workload significantly. 'The government
could solve this problem by either slimming down the national curriculum
immediately or by limiting the number of hours teachers could be called to
work.'
He indicated possible disagreement between the unions by saying the boycott
would end even if Sir Ron recommended introducing simple externally marked
'paper and pencil tests'.
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said
his union was taking action on educational content as well as workload.
