   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ASIL NADIR, the fugitive businessmen, attended six functions at Downing
Street during the 1980s, the prime minister disclosed last night, Philip
Stephens writes.
But in a series of parliamentary answers, Mr Major said that Mr Nadir had
not been invited to No 10 since Baroness Thatcher was replaced in November
1990.
Mr Major said that when he took office he halted the practice which had
allowed the Conservative party to host fundraising events in Downing Street.
He said that before that date a variety of political functions had taken
place at which the costs had been met by political parties.
Mr Nadir's visits to No 10 took place between 1984 and 1989, before the
collapse of his Polly Peck International business empire.
