<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Ministers may act against big water bill rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS may tell water companies to slow expensive improvements in order
to avoid sharp increases in water bills.
The proposal is likely to be part of the government's response to a report
by Ofwat, the water regulator, to be published next Tuesday. Industry
executives believe that the cost of industry improvements could be less than
the Pounds 43bn estimated by Ofwat in a similar report last year.
Mr David Luffrum, finance director of Thames Water, said yesterday: 'If
within the law it is possible to spread out the spending then we and our
customers would prefer that.' However, delaying some spending could bring
the UK into conflict with Brussels and could prove politically contentious
at home.
Improvements to drinking and bathing water quality have been among the most
popular European environmental rules, but the Ofwat report will fuel the
growing debate in the UK about whether the cost is too high.
One of the most controversial decisions facing ministers is whether to back
measures to remove the remaining traces of lead in drinking water, even
though this could cost Pounds 8bn.
Water companies have projected that bills will need to rise by about 6 per
cent above inflation between 1995 and 2000 to meet environmental rules. Next
spring, in the first wide-ranging review of the industry's pricing structure
since the 1989 privatisation, Ofwat will set price rises for 1995 to 2005.
Yesterday Mr Jim Gardner, chairman of Ofwat's national customer council,
called on the government to halt the increases in bills. He said that the
results of recent customer surveys 'give a strong message to the companies
and to government that customers are not prepared to pay even higher bills
for slightly better services'.
The estimate of Pounds 43bn in Ofwat's report, The Cost of Quality, did not
include the elimination of lead in drinking water, nor the statutory
water-quality objectives to be devised soon by the National Rivers
Authority. This year's report is based on more detailed projections by the
companies and on their customer surveys.
</TEXT>
