FT  06 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Union leaders search for progress
on party links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADERS of the two largest unions affiliated to the Labour party, the
TGWU and GMB general unions, yesterday both suggested ways to head off the
looming clash between the unions and the party leadership over union
representation in the party.
Mr John Edmonds, GMB general secretary, pressed the idea of postponing the
decision on how to select parliamentary candidates until next year's
conference as the Boundaries Commission findings makes a decision at this
year's conference unnecessary. Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, who wants
the unions excluded from local selections, has made clear, however, that he
does not favour postponement.
Meanwhile Mr Bill Morris, TGWU leader, speaking at the union's conference in
Bournemouth, said: 'If I was asked to advise Mr Smith I would just say 'talk
to us'. We have to have movement over the summer because the conference is
rapidly approaching'.
He floated the suggestion of a code of practice on how unions consult their
members paying the political levy over parliamentary selections and the
election of the leader.
He suggested that the code need not require ballots but could include
mem-bers voting at branches.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, who was attending the TGWU
conference, expressed interest in the idea of deferring a decision and in a
union code of practice. 'The important thing is we have to get an agreed
solution - there is good will on all sides,' she said.
</TEXT>
