<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Drive to reduce building litigation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A REVIEW to reduce contract abuses and litigation in the construction
industry was launched yesterday by Mr Tony Baldry, the environment minister.
Mr Baldry, a barrister, said more time was spent on litigation over building
defects than correcting them.
The inquiry, expected to cost Pounds 250,000, is to be financed jointly by
the government and construction employers' organisations. It will examine
ways to improve contractual and purchasing arrangements in the industry. It
will be led by Sir Michael Latham, a former Conservative MP who was director
of the Housebuilders Federation from 1971 to 1973.
Members of the inquiry team will include representatives of property
developers, main contractors and specialist sub-contractors.
Sir Michael said the review would take 12 months, with an interim report
planned for the end of this year.
The inquiry, proposed last summer by construction employers' organisations,
follows a series of complaints about builders from customers and from within
the industry.
Customers have complained about contractors trying to boost earnings by
claiming sometimes large additional payments for changes in the design or
specification of a building once construction has started.
The review is also expected to look at late payment of bills to contractors
and sub-contractors.
Mr Baldry said the review would examine ways to overhaul procedures to
reduce conflict and litigation and encourage productivity and
competitiveness.
He said lawyers recognised that construction provided the bulk of civil
actions in the courts and that this was a big drain on the industry and its
customers.
</TEXT>
