<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / M0 picks up after declining in April
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AMOUNT of money in circulation increased last month, pointing towards
continued economic revival.
Bank of England figures showed yesterday that M0, the narrow measure of the
money supply - mainly notes and coins in circulation - rose a
seasonally-adjusted 0.3 per cent compared with May after a fall of 1.1 per
cent in April.
This lifted the year-on-year growth rate to 4.4 per cent, an improvement on
May's exceptionally low figure of 3.3 per cent.
Analysts said the rebound in M0, which pushed the annual growth rate back
above the ceiling of the government's zero to 4 per cent monitoring range,
would allay fears that retail activity had dipped. The Bank said the fall in
May could have been linked to the two bank holidays in that month which
traditionally alter spending patterns.
Mr Robert Lind, economist at brokers UBS, said: 'The above-range growth in
M0 could presage a further recovery in retail sales in coming months. It
should also dampen speculation of an imminent cut in base rates.'
The Bank's figures also suggested that broad money growth - M0 plus bank
deposits - is on an upward trend from a low point of 3.1 per cent at the
start of the year. Seasonally-adjusted M4 rose by 0.5 per cent in May. The
year-on-year rate of increase was a seasonally-adjusted 3.8 per cent
compared with 3.5 per cent in April.
Strong M0 growth has been apparent since the start of the year. The
12-monthly growth rate recently peaked at 4.9 per cent in March, reflecting
the recovery in retail sales. Although there is no exact monthly
relationship between M0 and high street sales, the two follow similar paths.
In the latest six months on a year-on-year basis, M0 grew by 3.8 per cent.
The Bank revised slightly the figure for sterling lending to individuals and
companies by banks and building societies. In May this rose by Pounds 2bn
compared with a provisional Pounds 1.9bn.
</TEXT>
