<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / 'Ring of steel' relies on plastic bollards: Jimmy Burns
finds few obstacles as he ventures into the cordoned-off City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE BOOT of my car I carried a personal computer and a document bag, the
kind of luggage that when packed with Semtex explosive can shatter
buildings.
The police advice yesterday was to leave the car at home as London's
so-called ring of steel came into force. But out of necessity this City
worker had to take the risk.
In Belfast, a driver stopped at a checkpoint is automatically required to
produce some form of identification. An armed policeman or soldier conducts
the inquiry, while a back-up team of armed security personnel look on.
There, it is normal practice for the police or military to examine the
passenger seat and the boot, if the vehicle has been stopped in or near an
area identified as at high risk of terrorist attack.
London's version of street security proved slightly different. Starting off
from Wandsworth in south London at 8.30am, I took a route across the Thames
at Westminster and along the embankment into the Square Mile through one of
the permitted entry points in Cannon Street.
At the junction of Change Street and Cannon Street at 8.50am two policemen
stood by one of several entry points, a line of plastic bollards, waving
traffic on. Parked in one of the nearby sidestreets, closed now to through
traffic, a police squad car looked on discreetly. The traffic flowed
smoothlyon until it reached London Bridge.
Again no armed guards, just a couple of policemen flanked by photographers
and cameramen and a small group of protesters from an anti-militarist
movement. A very unmilitary looking City bobby somewhat self-consciously
checked a large van transporting stationery. His colleague questioned the
driver of a smaller van which was found to be empty. The checks caused the
kind of brief traffic snarl-up the City experiences on any working day and
which in Belfast has long been a fact of life.
Across the bridge thousands of commuters were marching unchallenged to work,
carrying briefcases and bags. The policemen had their eyes focused
exclusively on the vehicles.
It was now 9.10am. I had allowed the extra 30 minutes recommended by the
police and motoring organisations to get to work in time. With no real
congestion to speak of, I had arrived thirty minutes early, and with enough
time to put the effectiveness of the ring of steel further to the test.
The warning from the police was that nobody should attempt to drive around
or through the temporary barriers. Any irregular driving could set off a
security alert.
I drove back across London Bridge, past the same police squad car, and the
same police checkpoints.
I drove up to a road barrier (unmanned), tried to get round it, then backed
away. I turned off Cannon Street, negotiating the back streets which lie
behind the Lloyd's building. Here there were no policemen to be seen and
someone had parked unchallenged.
Just by Leadenhall Street, I stopped my own car, surveying the local
buildings, taking notes again. Nobody seemed remotely interested. I was
within a few city blocks of the site of the last big IRA bomb.
Editorial comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
