<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Ernst &amp; Young cleared by regulators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ERNST &amp; YOUNG, the accountancy firm, has been cleared of any deficiencies in
its current procedures and audit controls by the profession's regulators.
The Audit Registration Committee of the Institute of Chartered Accountants
in England and Wales concluded yesterday that it would propose no regulatory
action as a result of its investigation.
It emerged yesterday that at least three other public interest inquiries
into large accountancy firms are under way. One is believed to be at Price
Waterhouse, on which an announcement is imminent.
Yesterday's announcement signalled the conclusion of the Ernst &amp; Young
investigation, which was the first public interest inquiry to be conducted
by the commit-tee.
It followed criticism of the firm's audits and those of Arthur Young, with
which it has since merged, in several inquiries by Department of Trade and
Industry inspectors. These included audits of Sound Diffusion, Milbury,
Rotaprint and Edencorp Leisure.
The inquiries examine the adequacy of procedures and their documentation by
firms. But Mr Bruce Picking, director of practice regulation at the
institute, said it was far more difficult for its committee to review
professional judgment made during audits.
</TEXT>
