<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / MoD wants reliability and flexibility on a tight budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RELIABILITY, flexibility and maintenance are the themes of the defence white
paper as the Ministry of Defence stretches resources to meet commitments.
They are part of what Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, writes in his
introduction is 'a new and fundamental analysis of the way in which defence
assets are, and will need to be, employed'.
The starting point for this analysis is the three roles to be played by the
UK's defence forces:
Protection of territory. This ranges from patrolling territorial waters and
the streets of Northern Ireland to maintaining a nuclear capability.
Membership of Nato. This is to ensure against external threats to the UK and
its allies.
Promotion of wider interests. These include support for Nato, the Western
European Union and United Nations operations in the former Yugoslavia.
Each of these roles is then allocated personnel, equipment and budgets for
the next three years on the premise that 'the Warsaw Pact and the Soviet
Union now belong to history'.
The paper says the result is a number of adjustments, both enhancement and
reductions to force levels.
'The Navy's tasks can therefore be met by a force of 12 active submarines
rather than the 16 previously planned. We have therefore decided to withdraw
the Upholder Class of conventional submarine from service by 1995.'
It adds: 'Project definition studies continue for the replacement of the
assault ships Fearless and Intrepid, and we plan to invite tenders for the
refurbishment programme for the landing ship logistic Sir Bedivere shortly.'
Nuclear plans are practically unchanged 'to take account of the large
nuclear arsenal Russia will retain even after the implementation of Start
(Strategic Arms Reductions Talks) agreements'.
Each Trident submarine will initially carry no more than 128 Warheads,' the
paper says, although it says the figure may be reduced later.
The service life of the WE177 free-fall bomb is being extended 'well into
the next century' and a decision on its replacement postponed.
There is a reduction in equipment levels in the Royal Air Force. 'With
effect from 1 April 1994, a force of 100 Tornado F3 fighters will be fully
capable of defending the United Kingdom's airspace and meeting our
commitment to NATO's reaction forces - a reduction of 13 aircraft.'
These will be reorganised into six squadrons rather than the present seven.
The disappearance of the Warsaw Pact threat reduces the likelihood of bomber
attack. Therefore 'there is no near-term requirement for a medium-range
surface to air missile (MSAM).' The missile ws a Pounds 500m-plus contract
for which British companies had tendered.
But RAF transport aircraft and support helicopters receive promises of
orders. 'Substantial further investment in these areas is planned. This
includes the rolling replacement or refurbishment of about half the RAF's
Hercules fleet. There is a need to procure additional support helicopters.'
The Pounds 32bn Eurofighter 2000 project is regarded as 'keystone' of the
RAF's future capability, although the future of the Tornado GR1 is less
clear as the government continues to 'consider options for upgrading the
Tornado GR1 aircraft with a mid-life update which will enhance their
operational capability and allow their continued operation well into the
next century'.
Opponents of the abolition of some Army regiments received some good news.
'The previously announced amalgamations of the Royal Scots and the King's
Own Scottish Borderers, and of the Cheshire Regiment and the Staffordshire
Regiment, will not proceed.' The reversal of the decisions to amalgamate
these two regiments was made possible by 'reorganisation and efficiency
measures (to) release a further 2,000 personnel'.
But there are cuts in Army equipment. 'An indirect fire anti-armour missile
should be provided through the procurement of an air-launched weapon for the
RAF. This means that the United Kingdom will withdraw from the collaborative
programme to develop a ground-launched version of such a weapon (MLRS III).'
The effect of these changes will be 'more mobile, flexible armed forces. A
central feature of all new programmes is increased emphasis on reliability
and maintainability'.
The paper adds that the cut in defence spending to 3.2 per cent of gross
domestic product by 1995-96 leaves spending above the Nato average.
