<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Simpler reporting regime suggested
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTING Standards Board is considering plans to approve a simpler set
of financial reporting requirements for smaller British companies.
The initiative is designed to ease the burden on companies which would find
the board's new standards costly, and for which the public interest in
compliance is less essential.
It reflects concern from many companies that they will have difficulties in
implementing the ambitious and controversial programme of new standards
launched by the board.
Mr David Tweedie, the board's chairman, wrote this year suggesting the idea
to the Consultative Committee of Accounting Bodies, the body owned by the
leading pro-fessional accountancy bodies.
He said he hoped it would canvass the views of practitioners and smaller
companies, and possibly commission research on the topic.
The idea of a separate set of generally accepted accounting principles for
companies of different sizes has been debated in many countries, but few
have yet adopted such proposals. The Accounting Standards Board allowed
smaller companies to be temporarily exempt from FRS 1, its standard on the
cashflow statement which became mandatory last year.
Smaller companies are already exempt from supplying all but summary
financial information in the returns they are required to make public each
year at Companies House, the government's corporate information agency.
</TEXT>
