<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Patten makes switch in technology education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT funding will be made available to schools which specialise in
technology and can find sponsors from local businesses, Mr John Patten, the
education secretary, announced yesterday.
The move marks a shift from City Technology Colleges, which had previously
been at the centre of the government's attempts to encourage technology
teaching. CTCs were intended to be newly built schools, funded by the
private sector.
Employers' organisations, including the Confederation of British Industry,
objected that the government was attempting to raise funds from business
which could have come from the public sector. Only 14 CTCs have been built,
with another opening in September.
The new plan provides more government funding and is cheaper because it
utilises existing schools.
Mr Patten proposes that schools with local businesses represented on their
governing bodies should be backed with additional support from the
government, enabling the best of them to become technology colleges.
He said: 'Technology Colleges will be maintained schools specialising in
teaching technology, mathematics and science while still delivering the full
breadth of the national curriculum. They will adopt the best practices being
developed by the City Technology Colleges.'
The move received a frosty reception from teachers.
Mr Peter Smith, general secretary of the Association of Teachers and
Lecturers, said: 'Eventually, even this government will realise that what we
needed all along was better technology facilities in all schools, not just
their favourites.'
</TEXT>
