<HEADLINE>
FT  06 JUL 93 / Teachers to continue boycott of school tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK's two largest teachers' unions yesterday said their members would
continue boycotting national curriculum tests in September.
This intensifies pressure for drastic changes to the tests. A review of the
curriculum being conducted by Sir Ron Dearing, chairman designate of the
Schools Curriculum and Assessment Authority, is expected to produce
preliminary conclusions at the end of the month.
Boycotts by all three main teachers' unions this year meant that scarcely
any pupils took the tests.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, made clear that his union would stop
the boycott if the review reduced their workload significantly. 'The boycott
will be rescinded if the promised reduction in workload is delivered on the
ground. The government could solve this problem by either slimming down the
national curriculum immediately or by limiting the number of hours teachers
could be called to work. These hours are currently unlimited.'
Mr de Gruchy indicated possible disagreement between the unions by adding
that the boycott would end even if Sir Ron recommended introducing simple
externally marked 'paper and pencil tests', although the union opposed them
on educational grounds.
He said that this would not provide legal backing for industrial action,
although it would take other measures, such as asking parents to withdraw
their children from the tests.
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said
his union was taking action over objections to the tests' educational
content as well as workload. 'The boycott remains in place as long as the
assessment and testing arrangements remain,' he said.
</TEXT>
