FT  06 JUL 93 / Bosnia sniper kills British aid worker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BRITISH woman aid worker and an 11-year-old girl were killed yesterday in
fresh violence in Sarajevo, as conditions continued to deteriorate in the
besieged Bosnian capital, report Laura Silber and Agencies.
The aid worker, named by the Foreign Office in London as Christine Witcutt,
56, was shot by a sniper as she was driving out of the city in a truck
emblazoned with the words 'Don't shoot'. She worked for the Edinburgh Direct
Aid private charity.
Her husband was driving another truck in a convoy of six vehicles that had
taken relief supplies to Sarajevo at the weekend.
The girl who died was one of 12 children hit by exploding mortar bombs
during a renewed Serbian bombardment of the city. She died on the operating
table of a hospital.
Relief workers said the situation in the city was becoming unbearable, with
hospitals unable to keep blood plasma without power to run refrigerators. UN
officials have expressed grave concern about the possible outbreak of
typhoid and cholera because of the lack of electricity and running water.
Meanwhile, Gen Rasim Delic, commander of the Moslem-led Bosnian army,
ordered his troops to grant safe passage to two Bosnian Croat commanders
blockaded inside a Canadian UN base in central Bosnia. Sarajevo radio said
United Nations officials mediated their release in exchange for four Moslems
held by Croat troops.
Mrs Danielle Mitterrand, wife of the French president, arrived in Belgrade
yesterday to appeal for the release of arrested opposition chief Vuk
Draskovic and his wife Danica.
